comments.body:
@iSazonov I think this is a separate issue. It may turn out to be related to path normalization, but I still think it should have it's own issue.

This one is about attempting to rename, remove or move an *existing* file. The error message in this case is `Cannot find path '1\2' because it does not exist.` rather than `Could not find a part of the path 'C:\temp\1\2'`.

I think you'd be unlikely to run into this in Windows, at least on its native file systems, since both forward and backslashes are disallowed. In Unix forward slashes are allowed, and it's simple create, from bash or other programs, a file with forward slashed in the name.

@iSazonov I would love to see this based on file system type rather than platform, along with a number of other areas. One problem is that I haven't found a way to definitively identify an NTFS file system under Linux.

Regarding `[System.IO.Path]::GetInvalidPathChars()` and `[System.IO.Path]::GetInvalidFileNameChars()`, there appear to be separate implementations for each *platform* in coreclr.

It seems that the notion of illegal characters is largely platform-based rather than file system based. As an experiment, I created a file named `a>b<c:?|` on an NTFS volume on my Linux box with the `touch` command. There are five characters in there that Windows considers to be illegal, but the NTFS file system accepts them and Windows displays the file properly in Windows Explorer. I can't *do* anything with it on Windows, such open or delete it, but it is recognized.

I ran into this issue while trying to download files from Azure Blob Storage. On Windows, it was creating directories properly for blobs with slashes, but on unix systems it was creating files with backslashes in their names instead. Here is the function I wrote to build a directory structure out of the files in the directory.

For example, given a file with the name `foo\bar\baz.txt`, the directories `./foo/bar/` will be created with a `baz.txt` file in it.

Hopefully this helps someone out.

```powershell
function Repair-DirectoriesForUnixSystems($directory) {
    if ($IsWindows) {
        return;
    }

    $filesWithBackslashes = @(Get-ChildItem $directory | Where Name -like '*\*')

    foreach ($file in $filesWithBackslashes) {
        $split = $file.FullName.Split("\")

        $directoryNames = $split[0..($split.Length - 2)]

        $path = $directoryNames -join "/"

        if (-not (Test-Path $path)) {
            New-Item -Path $path -Type Directory > $null
        }

        $fileName = $split[$split.Length - 1]

        # NOTE: the native unix copy and remove must be used because of this issue
        # https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/issues/3666
        & cp $file.FullName "$path/$fileName"
        & rm $file.FullName
    }
}
```
